<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Discrete_geometry&action=edit&section=1.php.html" title="Edit section: History">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span></h2>
<p>Although <a href="Polyhedra" title="Polyhedra" class="mw-redirect">polyhedra</a> and <a href="Tessellation" title="Tessellation">tessellations</a> have been studied for many years by people such as <a href="Johannes_Kepler" title="Johannes Kepler">Kepler</a> and <a href="Augustin-Louis_Cauchy" title="Augustin-Louis Cauchy">Cauchy</a>, modern discrete geometry has its origins in the late 19th century. Early topics studied were: the density of <a href="Circle_packing" title="Circle packing">circle packings</a> by <a href="Axel_Thue" title="Axel Thue">Thue</a>, <a href="Projective_configuration" title="Projective configuration" class="mw-redirect">projective configurations</a> by Reye and <a href="Ernst_Steinitz" title="Ernst Steinitz">Steinitz</a>, the <a href="Geometry_of_numbers" title="Geometry of numbers">geometry of numbers</a> by Minkowski, and <a href="Four_colour_theorem" title="Four colour theorem" class="mw-redirect">map colourings</a> by Tait, Heawood, and Hadwiger.</p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Discrete_geometry&action=edit&section=2.php.html" title="Edit section: Topics in discrete geometry">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Topics_in_discrete_geometry">Topics in discrete geometry</span></h2>
